.START 

British Airways PLC gave details of its $750 million investment in Airlines Acquisition Corp., the vehicle set up to take over UAL Corp. 

The British airline, which plans to take a 15% share in the Chicago-based parent of United Airlines upon completion of the proposed merger, said it will receive various convertible preferred shares in return for its cash investment. 

British Airways said it will receive $250 million of non-dividend-bearing Airline Acquisition preferred stock.
The shares can be converted at any time into common of the acquired UAL and will be equal to 15% of its shareholder equity. 

It said it will also receive $200 million of preferred carrying a dividend of 13% annually.
The dividends will be payable in cash, but British Airways said it agreed to reinvest the dividends in the U.S. airline holding company for the first five years. 

The remainder will be in the form of $300 million of preferred carrying a dividend of 18% annually.
As with the 13% dividend shares, British Airways agreed to reinvest its dividends for five years. 

